Experiment performed at the Oak Ridge
National Laboratory's Holifield Radioactive Ion Beam
Facility using the Isotope Separator On-line (ISOL)
technique.
The detection system was made up of
six telescopes and each consisted of a dE detector
followed by an E detector, both with area of 5x5 cm2.
The dE detectors have 16 strips and are position
sensitive while the rear detectors were pads that
simply measured energy. Detector telescopes allowed
for energy measurement as well as both position
determination and particle identification

Experiment performed at the Oak Ridge
National Laboratory's Holifield Radioactive Ion Beam
Facility using the Isotope Separator On-line (ISOL)
technique.
Atoms of 18F were produced via the 16O(alpha,pn)18F
reaction at energy of 85 MeV using HfO2 target. The
HfO2 target was in fibrous form and was heated for
fast diffusion of 18F atoms out of the target. The
fluorine atoms produced diffuse through the target
material and effuse through a transport line to the
cesium ion source to be negatively ionized. The beam
passes through two stages of mass separation before
injection into a 25-MV tandem electrostatic accelerator
dE-E method was used for particle
identification and coincidence between alpha
particles and heavy fragments was required
Inverse kinematics was used
CD2 target with thickness of 716 mu-g/cm2
